# Text-to-Speech Tool Walkthrough

## What Was Built
I have implemented the Python-based Text-to-Speech (TTS) tool with a Pywebview GUI customized for a mobile screen size (400x700).

- **UI-main**: Includes standard controls (Language selection, Start index). The 'Play' and 'Save' buttons remain disabled until content is loaded and processed.
- **UI-load**: Includes intuitive controls to load text files natively using system dialogues or via screen-scraping web pages using `BeautifulSoup`.
- **Text Processing**: Uses robust Natural Language Toolkit (`nltk` punkt tokenizer) to accurately splice text into separate sentences once loaded from either source.
- **Playback & Stop**: Added full playback utilizing Google TTS (`gTTS`). When Play is pushed, audio sentences stream using `pygame.mixer` one-by-one, automatically advancing the start index on the UI. The loop runs in a background daemon thread so the UI remains fluid. Pressing 'Stop' cleanly breaks the loop and halts `pygame` playback mid-sentence.
- **Audio Caching**: Audio processing is optimized by saving gTTS `mp3` files to a temporary directory. If you replay the same text/index configuration, the cached MP3 is directly streamed, skipping the slow internet request to Google TTS.
- **Clear Cache**: Added a "Clear" button to the main UI which wipes all temporary `.mp3` TTS files from your system temp folder.
- **Save Functionality**: Sentences are saved line-by-line using a system dialogue when the user wishes to export the payload.

